 Basse-Normandie, France":"Marigny, Manche, Lower Normandy, France","Thiel-sur-Acolin, Allier, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, France":"Thiel-sur-Acolin, Allier, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Traînel","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (northern): occupational name for a trapper, from Middle English <i>trainer</i> ‘trapper of wild animals’, an agent derivative of <i>trainen</i> ‘to set a trap or snare’. See   Train   and compare   Trapp  .","Irish (Armagh): variant of   Trainor  .","Altered form of German <b>Trainer</b>, a habitational name for someone from Train in Bavaria or Trainau in Upper Franconia."],"variants":[{"name":"Trainor","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Aidan, Brendan, Ciaran, Finbar.","Irish (Ulster): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Tréinfhir</b> ‘son of <i>Tréanfhear</i>’, a byname meaning ‘warrior, champion’, from <i>tréan</i> ‘strong’ + <i>fear</i> ‘man’.","English (Lancashire): variant of   Trainer  ."]},{"name":"Train","meanings":["English:","from Middle English <i>train(e)</i> ‘trap, snare’ (Old French <i>traine</i>), perhaps a nickname for a trapper. See   Trainer  .","nickname from northern Middle English <i>tran(e)</i> ‘crane’ (Old Norse <i>trani</i>), perhaps also used as a personal name."]}]},{"name":"Agnès","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Agnès de Traînel was born in 1250, her father, Garnier de Traînel V, was 31 and her mother, Aremburg d'Epoisses, was 21. She had at least 1 son with Pons Poincet de Thil. She died in Marigny, Manche, Lower Normandy, France."},"et":{"1250–":"1250–Surnud","1250–Female":"1250–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1245–Male":"1245–Surnud","1275–1317":"1275–1317","1220–1266":"1220–1266","1230–1268":"1230–1268","1268":"1268","1245":"1245","1266":"1266","1275":"1275","1220":"1220","1230":"1230","1250":"1250","1317":"1317","Marigny, Manche, Basse-Normandie, France":"Marigny, Manche, Basse-Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Thiel-sur-Acolin, Allier, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, France":"Thiel-sur-Acolin, Allier, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1250–":"1250–Kuollut","1250–Female":"1250–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1245–Male":"1245–Kuollut","1275–1317":"1275–1317","1220–1266":"1220–1266","1230–1268":"1230–1268","1268":"1268","1245":"1245","1266":"1266","1275":"1275","1220":"1220","1230":"1230","1250":"1250","1317":"1317","Marigny, Manche, Basse-Normandie, France":"M